@drcrallen I've posted benchmark times in the first message in this thread, compare `V9` (51..., 49...) and `V9Optimized` (43..., 41...). Or you mean something different?

There couldn't be a big difference depending on the system, because this optimization is only about managed, on-heap JVM data structures and operations with them. Only the ratio of time spent in OS/JVM could be different in different systems, but it couldn't completely turn the effect of the change. However, in the PR intruducing this benchmark (https://github.com/druid-io/druid/pull/2875) @jon-wei  posted similar results (52..45 vs 51..49).

The question to Druid committers remain: in what form should be this PR: some code copied from fastutil into the Druid codebase, or introducing a dep?

@kaijianding IMO if there's a global limit it's fine to hit every data node and just throw away some data past the limit. This isn't optimal performance wise, _but_ I think that the common use case for scan is likely to be with no limit and/or with hitting data nodes directly. So, I think it's okay if we don't fully optimize for the case where there is a limit and the query hits a broker.

I think caching is unnecessary, so we can just return a null caching strategy.

Docs and tests are important though.

@fjy I'm ok with committing to this as a core feature of druid rather than a contrib extension if the authors are into that. It seems like it'd be useful for integrating Druid with other systems.

